ocial norms. Yet it is the skewed relation to the temporal norm that also gives queerness its singular hope. This is demonstrated by the essays collected here as they consider the ways in which queer theory has acknowledged, resisted, appropriated, or refused divergent models of temporality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHomosexuality and literature. 0aHomosexuality and motion pictures. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aHomosexuality in motion pictures. 0aQueer theory. 0aTime in literature. 0aTime in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Lesbian / Gay Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh1 aAhmed, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruhm, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColebrook, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDean, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallop, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalberstam, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuciano, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarriott, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCallum, E. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCallum, E. L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOhi, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRohy, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary